renames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Deighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Durham): habitational name from any of several places in Yorkshire named Deighton, from Old English <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch, dike’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement, enclosure’. See also   Ditton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ditton","meanings":["English (Kent): habitational name from any of numerous places called Ditton, for example Ditton in Kent, Buckinghamshire, and Lancashire; Fen Ditton or Wood Ditton in Cambridgeshire; or Thames Ditton or Long Ditton in Surrey, all from Old English <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch, dike’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement, farmstead’."]},{"name":"Deaton","meanings":["English (Middlesex): variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dinsdale","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Over Dinsdale (North Yorkshire) or Low Dinsdale (Durham), which stand on opposite sides of the Tees river. The name arises from Old English <i>Dīctūneshalh</i> ‘nook, recess (Old English <i>halh</i>) belonging to   Deighton  ’."]},{"name":"Deyton","meanings":["English: variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dighton","meanings":["English (Huntingdonshire): variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dayton","meanings":["English: variant of   Deighton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert de Deighton was born about 1275, in England, United Kingdom. She married Robert de Deighton about 1300. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"about 1275–":"umbes 1275–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1304":"1304","1300":"1300","Abt 1304":"umbes 1304","1275":"1275","1383":"1383","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1275":"umbes 1275","Abt 1306":"umbes 1306","abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1306":"1306","Deighton, Yorks, Eng":"Deighton, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Deighton, Yorkshire, England":"Deighton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Deighton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Deighton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", Yorks, Eng":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1275–":"noin 1275–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1304–Male":"1304–Kuollut","1306–Male":"1306–Kuollut","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1300":"1300","Abt 1304":"noin 1304","1275":"12